Gerry,<br><br>
Thanks for the words of encouragement. It is difficult to be objective about ones self. The words of a trusted individual are always valued, such as yours.<br><br>
You are right on about the fallout. As I look back, I see a very disheartening image. I have adversely influenced many people, rightfully or wrongfully, for reasons that do not often connect with reality as most experience it. Therein lies the disconnect. My &quot;reality&quot; is sometimes colored to an extreme that reflects defensive and offensive strategies no longer appropriate to the situation at hand. Yes, at some level, I am always back in Vietnam, and the &quot;enemy&quot; is transformed by slight of mind into the object of destructive mechanistic corrective action. Sometimes, things happen for no apparent reason other than internal torment, and I experience flashbacks which really turn inward and feed upon myself. I am now painfully aware of these things as I learn to recognize the signs of transformation and begin to use techniques to return to the land of the here and now. I am not at all perfect, and I slip many times, but the times I succeed will grow with patience.<br><br>
The most amazing part of all this is my new found ability to acknowledge what I have learned about myself, what I am, and what I am doing about it. I chose, of all places, a forum open to the entire global community. Do not think I am embued with bravery, for an element of fear pervades this very act. I feel I am discovering what I am, and I am no longer as ashamed if it as I once was. I am a Vietnam Veteran. My problems were acquired by circumstances completely beyond control, and it is that, too, which I have begun to understand and acknowledge.<br><br>
HELLO, WORLD!<br><br>
(You too, Doc Spatz.)
